#                         COE5 CLASS DATA IN MOD FORMAT
# 
# This file contains the class data for CoE5, extracted from the executable. 
# Although this file is not actually a mod, its contents adhere to CoE5's
# modding format in order to make it an optimal resource for modders.
# 
# This file provides examples of how base game classes can be built using
# modding commands (although some classes in the base game do use some commands
# that are not available to modders) and templates that modders can use to
# create their own classes.
# 
# Everything to the right of a "#" (such as what you're reading now) is a
# comment, which means the game ignores it; it's there as a note for human
# readers (i.e. you).  I've provided comments toward the right of many lines to
# explain various things, but since I expect the class data to be mostly of
# interest to modders, I assume the reader has also read the modding manual and
# is familiar with at least the most common class modding commands described
# therein.
# 
# If a line begins with "# fx" followed by a number, that means it's either a
# command that isn't accessible to modders, or I haven't taught the app to
# translate it yet (or both).  I present these as comments because they don't
# have mod command names that the game would recognize (so to adhere to the
# modding format, I need to tell it to ignore them), but the part that's
# actually intended for humans to read is the second comment, to the right. 
# Two examples:
# 
# fx226             4 # [flagterr]: Ancient Forest. Can flag this terrain even
# if unable to collect any of its income.
# 
# fx208             1 # Unhandled trait 208 with argument 1.
# 
# The first example is a command that isn't accessible to modders.  You can
# safely ignore everything to the left of the second "#".  The word in [] is my
# guess at what Illwinter might call this command if they did make it
# accessible to modders.  Everything after that is my explanation of what it
# does; in this case, it allows players of this class to flag Ancient Forests
# even if the player doesn't have any units that can collect any of the
# resources generated by Ancient Forests.
# 
# The second example is a command the app doesn't know how to translate (you
# can recognize these by the words "Unhandled" or "Unknown").  Unless you want
# to guess at their meanings, you can ignore these, other than to remember that
# there's some detail about the class that isn't explained yet.
# 
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 
#                           INFORMATION FOR MODDERS
# 
#                             Class Modding Maxima
# 
# Each class has reserved space for 1 (and only 1) each of the following
# commands: setclassname, classdescr, classabdescr, setmaincom, hometerr,
# townbonusdescr, libbonusdescr, and templebonusdescr.
# 
# Each class has reserved space for 4 instances of the addstartterr command
# (you can use less, but not more).
# 
# Each class has room for 16 total addstartunits and / or addstartcom commands
# (you can use however many of each command you want, so long as there are no
# more than 16 total between the two of them).
# 
# Each class has room for 16 fx commands.  Most class modding commands not
# already mentioned here will use up one of the class's fx command slots. 
# Exceptions (at the time I write this) include: selectclass, newclass,
# clearstartterr, clearstartunits, and the commands for modding class
# recruitment lists (clearrec, addunitrec, addmercrec, addcomrec, recxcost,
# templerec, libraryrec, and reclimiter), which are technically separate data
# structures from classes.
# 
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 
#                                    CREDITS
# 
# - Illwinter Game Design, for the creation of the wonderful Conquest of
# Elysium and Dominions games in general, and specifically for the creation of
# CoE5, from which all data in this file was extracted.  Also for the creation
# of the modding manual, which named the commands, was useful in helping to
# differentiate commands, and from which some descriptions in this file were
# copied or adapted.
# 
# - Marlin, for publishing (for CoE4) documentation identifying some class fx
# IDs.  While many remained unidentified and many more have been added in CoE5,
# his work saved me some time, and I appreciate it!
# 
# - Me, Colonel Dracula joins the Navy, for deciphering everything in the class
# data except the fx IDs identified by Marlin and for extracting and
# translating the data.
# 
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

newclass  #  1
setclassname "Baron"
classdescr "The frontiers of the human realm were defended by landowners known as Barons.  Some Barons were warlike and restless.  As humankind spread over Elysium and became dominant, these barons tried to usurp their masters' powers and waged war on their neighbors.  The large, well-trained forces at their disposal made them formidable foes.  They were soon in control of large parts of the human territories.  However, not all humans were content with this.  The sorcerers of Elysium gathered armies of their own and nonhuman warlords called out for vengeance.  The Barons must once again subjugate Elysium.

The Baron has a wide variety of human troops and huge siege engines at his disposal.  Knights are formidable units who can inflict additional damage by charging enemies in the initial phase of a battle.  Heavy infantry units are strong, but move slowly.  Fast cavalry units under the leadership of mounted commanders work as highly mobile forces.

The Baron knows how to keep his subjects in line and can cow peasants into obedience.  All farms and villages under the Baron's rule are required to send a levy of soldiers to the Baron each year.  This muster consists of simple spearmen from farms and at least one knight from each village.  Large towns and cities do not contribute soldiers.  The Baron can also form local militias to defend villages and cities.  The larger the settlement, the stronger the militia."
classabdescr "Starts in a very well fortified castle.
25% increase to gold income.
25% increase to iron income.
Conscription yields soldiers from settlements and ancient forests once every year.
The Baron and High Lords can raise levies (stationary defenders) in villages and towns.
Receives free units from Guard Towers."
hometerr           30 # Baron's Castle
addstartterr        5 # Farm
addstartterr        6 # Farm
addstartterr        7 # Hamlet
setmaincom             "Baron"
addstartunits          "Spearman"                  6
addstartunits          "Longbowman"                5
addstartcom            "High Lord"
addstartunits          "Cavalryman"                5
recherochance       1 # Chance for recruitment offers from human heroes.
recasschance        2 # Chance for recruitment offers from human assassins.
# fx226             4 # [flagterr]: Ancient Forest. Can flag this terrain even if unable to collect any of its income.
# fx226             8 # [flagterr]: Enchanted Forest. Can flag this terrain even if unable to collect any of its income.
